    Problem 2 â€” Search pop-up unstyled &amp; duplicate buttons


      Click to reveal solution

        Root cause&nbsp;A (duplicate icons)
        â€¢ Butterfly already injects #search-button on the right.
        â€¢ A second custom &lt;li&gt; a#search-toggle was added in the menu.
        â†’ Remove either trigger (keep stock one for simplicity).
        Root cause&nbsp;B (CSS not loading)
        â€¢ custom-search.css rendered to public/css/ but wasnâ€™t linked.
        â€¢ The YAML key was mis-typed (inject. / smart quotes).
        Fix
        1.&nbsp;Move stylesheet to source/css/custom-search.css.
        2.&nbsp;In themes/butterfly/_config.yml add:

inject:
&nbsp;&nbsp;head:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- &lt;link&nbsp;rel="stylesheet"&nbsp;href="/css/custom-search.css"&gt;

        3.&nbsp;hexo clean &amp;&amp; hexo g â‡’
        &lt;link&gt; now appears in&nbsp;&lt;head&gt; â†’ styles apply.







      0














    Problem 3 â€” Which way to load extra CSS / JS?

      Click to reveal solution
      Two paths in Butterfly / Hexo

        themes/butterfly/_config.yml â–º inject:
            Site-wide.  Use when every page must see the file.
            &nbsp;&nbsp;â€¢ head:&nbsp;â€”&nbsp;CSS or critical JS (loads before paint)
            &nbsp;&nbsp;â€¢ bottom:&nbsp;â€”&nbsp;Non-blocking JS (loads just before &lt;/body&gt;)
        css: / js: lists in a pageâ€™s front-matter
            Local. Only that post/page gets the links. Ideal for page-specific
            widgets, diagrams, slide decks, etc.

      Applied fix (Search modal skin)
# themes/butterfly/_config.yml
inject:
  head:
    - &lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/custom-search.css"&gt;

      That stylesheet now loads on every page, before the modal HTML is
         rendered, so the search dialog inherits the new glass-morphism look.





      0












    Problem&nbsp;4 â€” Give one page its own banner image

      Click to reveal solution

        In the markdown front-matter add:
        top_img: /img/my_banner.jpg
        &nbsp;â€¢ Works for posts and pages.
        &nbsp;â€¢ Use top_img: false to hide the banner entirely.
        &nbsp;â€¢ Global fallbacks stay in _config.butterfly.yml.





      0












    Problem&nbsp;5 â€” Re-skin the white â€œmiddle cardâ€ on one page

      Click to reveal solution

        Load a page-specific style-sheet (either via css: front-matter
        or a raw &lt;link&gt; tag) and paint #content-inner:

        /* /css/about-bg.css â€” linked on /about/ only */
        #content-inner&#123;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;background:linear-gradient(135deg,#ffecd2 0%, #fcb69f 100%) !important;
        &#125;
        #page&#123; background:transparent !important; &#125;

        Because the CSS file is loaded only here, the rule never touches other pages.





      0













    Problem&nbsp;6 â€” æŽ§åˆ¶å…¨å±€èƒŒæ™¯Replace the global purple backdrop only on About

      Click to reveal solution

        The colour comes from #body-wrap&#123;background:#2E294E;&#125;.
        Override it in the About-only CSS file:

        /* in /css/about-bg.css */
        #body-wrap&#123;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;background:linear-gradient(135deg,#ffecd2 0%, #fcb69f 100%) !important;
        &#125;
        #body-wrap::before&#123; background:none !important; &#125; /* removes mask */

        Key point: !important and equal/higher specificity
        are required to beat the themeâ€™s global rule.





      0












     Problem&nbsp;7 â€” åˆ›å»ºpageå­é¡µé¢æŒ‡ä»¤ Create /album/2025/05/ with one Hexo command

         Click to reveal solution

             Hexo treated every string after hexo&nbsp;new&nbsp;page as a single
             slug. That turned album/2025/05 into
             album-2025-05 and dropped the file in
             source/album-2025-05/index.md. Two quick ways to place the file
             exactly where we want are:


             A.&nbsp;Slug + custom path

                 hexo&nbsp;new&nbsp;page&nbsp;05&nbsp;--path&nbsp;album/2025/05/index.md

             Same result, but lets you pick a friendlier title for the page front-matter.


             Key point:&nbsp;Hexo escapes slashes in the slug unless you
             explicitly tell it that â€œindexâ€ is part of the path or supply
             --path.
             After generating, run hexo&nbsp;clean&nbsp;&amp;&amp;&nbsp;hexo&nbsp;g
             so the new page appears at /album/2025/05/.






